  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony under both federal and state laws in the United States, as well as in many other countries. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally gained proceeds (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin.\n\n### In the United States:\n- **Federal Law:** The primary federal statute addressing money laundering is the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). \n  - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** makes it a felony to engage in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to promote further criminal activity, conceal the nature of the proceeds, or avoid reporting requirements.\n  - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** makes it a felony to engage in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property worth more than $10,000.\n\n- Penalties: Convictions under these statutes can result in severe penalties, including up to **20 years in prison**, substantial fines (often in the hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars), and forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\n### State Laws:\n- Most states also have their own money laundering laws, which can carry additional penalties. The specifics vary by state, but the crime is typically classified as a felony, punishable by imprisonment and fines.\n\n### International Context:\n- Many countries have strict anti-money laundering laws, and international cooperation exists through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. Penalties in other jurisdictions can also include significant prison sentences and fines.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense, and those convicted can face severe legal consequences.",
